<div id="main">
<br>
<a href="http://www.isoc-au.org.au">ISOC-AU</a>,
<a href="http://www.ac3.com.au">ac3</a>,
<a href="http://www.smartinternet.com.au">Smart Internet</a>, and
<a href="http://www.grangenet.net">GrangeNet</a>
hosted the forum <b>Designing the Future 2005</b> in Sydney
on <b>Wednesday 6th April 2005</b>,
which focussed on the implications of massive Internet bandwidth for 
business, medicine, education, communities and the IT industry.

<p>
<a href="abstracts.html"><b>It was a fascinating and thought-provoking
day, and here are the abstracts and links to
the speakers' presentation slides</b></a>.
<p>
DTF'05 was the definitive portrayal of the evolving global Internet in
2005, showcasing the imminent developments going mainstream over the
next few years.  Our speakers had a vast range of experience exploring
massive bandwidth in the real world, from remote diagnostics to black
holes, from new networks to entertainment and hyperculture.

<p>
The entire event was successfully broadcast over the Internet using the
Access Grid ("video-conferencing on steroids").  We wrapped up with a
live concert over the Access Grid with a difference: jazz musicians in
far-apart cities playing together beautifully.

<p>
With many thanks to to our speakers for their thoughtful contributions, 
and to our sponsors - Cisco, Intel, Optus, Powertel and DCITA
- for supporting such an interesting event!

</div>

